## Introduction and Context
### Introduction
Throughout this semester, our group worked on designing Eunoia, a
mental-health-centered productivity app for students dealing with academic stress,
burnout, and inconsistent routines. Instead of creating another productivity app that
simply pushes users to be more efficient, we focused on building something that
responds to how a student is actually feeling. Working on this project pushed us to look
beyond features and screens and think more carefully about the emotional, behavioral,
and systemic factors that shape productivity.

### Context
This problem space is both personal and widely shared. As a student, I have experienced
days where motivation and focus change even when I genuinely want to stay productive.
These challenges are not just about poor time management or lack of discipline, but are
closely tied to mental health, workload pressure, and unrealistic expectations. Many
existing productivity tools ignore this reality and assume users can operate at the same
level every day, which can make falling behind feel even more discouraging. Eunoia
started from the question of how a productivity tool could feel more supportive instead
of adding pressure.

### Paper Overview
This paper reflects on the design and development of Eunoia through three key concepts
from IS 340: Wicked Problems, Human-in-the-Loop systems, and Planning as an
iterative design practice. Rather than focusing only on what we built, this paper looks at
how these concepts shaped our decisions and guided our thinking throughout the
project. Each concept helped us question our assumptions, navigate tradeoffs, and
design a system that remains flexible and centered on the user.
### Principles

#### Principle 1: Wicked Problems
Student mental health and productivity is an example of a wicked problem. Rather than
having a single solution, this problem is shaped by overlapping factors such as academic
pressure, personal expectations, mental health, social obligations, and changing day to
day circumstances. These factors constantly shift, meaning that what works for one
student or even for the same student on one day may not work the next. Understanding
this complexity early on changed how we approached the design of Eunoia.
At the beginning of the project, it was tempting to think about productivity in a more
simplified way by designing a system that could help students optimize their time,
complete more tasks, and establish a consistent routine. However, viewing the problem
through the lens of wicked problems forced us to take a step back. Recognizing that
productivity is not a one time fix allowed us to shift our focus from making the app
optimal to making it adaptable. Applying this concept directly shaped several design
decisions within Eunoia. Rather than assuming students would feel motivated or
focused every day, we designed the app to adjust based on how they are feeling. Daily
check -ins allow the system to recognize a student’s mental state before recommending a
work session instead of forcing them into a rigid schedule. This approach reflects the
idea that productivity challenges are not problems that need to be fixed, but ongoing
experiences that require flexibility and understanding. Recognizing student productivity
as a wicked problem also changed how we defined success within the project. Instead of
focusing on how many tasks a user completed or how long they worked, we started
paying more attention to sustainability and habit building. Small wins, shorter work
sessions, and positive reinforcement became more meaningful than pushing students to
maximize output. This shift helped make sure that the design supported students over
time rather than adding to burnout. Overall, thinking about wicked problems reshaped
how I approached this project. It reinforced the idea that some problems are not meant to
be solved once, but supported through thoughtful, adaptable design that acknowledges
complexity instead of trying to eliminate it.

#### Principle 2: Human in the Loop
Another key concept that shaped the design of Eunoia was the idea of a Human in the
Loop system. Rather than allowing a system to make decisions entirely on its own, a
Human in the Loop approach keeps students actively involved in the process. This
concept was especially important for our project because productivity and mental health
are deeply personal. Allowing a system to fully automate decisions in this space could
easily feel controlling, impersonal, or even harmful. Thinking through this concept early
on also changed how we approached control within the app. Instead of letting Eunoia
automatically decide how long a student should work or when they should take breaks,
we focused on designing a system that works alongside the user. The app offers
recommendations based on daily check -ins, but students always have the ability to
adjust, ignore, or override those suggestions. This balance helped the system feel
supportive and flexible rather than controlling or restrictive. Through this process, I
realized that effective design is not about maximizing automation or removing people
from the process, but about maintaining a thoughtful balance between guidance and
user choice. In the context of Eunoia, keeping users involved at every step helped create
an experience that feels more personal and adaptable. This reinforced my belief that
good design should support users while still giving them meaningful control.

#### Principle 3: Planning as an Iterative Design Practice
Planning shaped much of how Eunoia grew throughout the semester, but we never
treated it as a concrete roadmap. From the start, we viewed planning as something
flexible that would shift as we learned more and as the project evolved. This mindset
kept us open to feedback, helped us pivot when ideas did not work as expected, and
allowed us to keep moving forward without getting stuck or discouraged. Iteration
became a core part of how we evaluated and strengthened the design. Each feedback
checkpoint informed the next version of Eunoia and surfaced issues we could not see at
the beginning. Rather than treating mistakes as setbacks, we saw them as signals that
the design needed to change. This approach made the project stronger over time and
reinforced the idea that good planning is not about predicting every outcome, but about
responding thoughtfully as new information emerges. Working through this process
also changed how I think about design more broadly. I realized that effective planning is
not about ignoring missed signals or forcing ideas to work, but about learning how to
adapt when those signals appear. Allowing the design to evolve in this way helped make
sure that Eunoia more accurately reflected students’ real needs rather than an idealized
version of how productivity should look.

### Conclusion
Viewing student productivity and mental health as a wicked problem reinforced the idea
that there is no single solution that works for everyone. Instead, it pushed us to prioritize
flexibility and long term support over one size fits all approaches. Applying a Human in
the Loop framework further emphasized the importance of user agency, trust, and
ethical responsibility, especially when working with emotionally sensitive experiences.
Treating planning as an iterative practice allowed the project to evolve through feedback,
testing, and reflection rather than being constrained by a rigid plan. Together, these
principles shaped not only the final design of Eunoia, but also how I now think about
design more broadly. This project helped me realize that effective design is less about
control or perfection and more about responsiveness, care, and adaptability. Rather than
trying to solve complex problems outright, meaningful design supports people as they
navigate change. Moving forward, these concepts will continue to guide how I approach
problem solving, system design, and user centered experiences.

